{Welcome to this course on the 'Frankenstein-Dracula' variation of the Vienna 
Game. I've taken the unusual step of giving different variations from different 
color perspectives, as I firmly believe the best way to understand a chess 
opening (among other things) is from the perspective of both sides. In general, 
when the variation given favors White, it will be presented from White's 
perspective and vice-versa, and when the variation is equal/unclear, I've mostly 
presented it from White's perspective as a 'default'. In any event, please feel 
free to send me feedback about this or anything else about this course - a chess 
opening is very much a 'living document' and I expect to update it in future as 
it continues to evolve. Thank you, - John Chernoff} 1. -- *

[Event "Vienna Game: Frankenstein-Dracula Variation"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "vienna-game-frankenstein-dracula-variation/course/29512, variation/5197513"]

{Welcome to this course on one of the most complex if not downright 
controversial of openings: the 'Frankenstein Dracula' variation. As we shall 
see, the positions that arise from this opening defy easy explanation. In fact, 
even computers tend to require quite a bit of time to unearth many of the hidden 
ideas buried deep within, waiting until the witching hour to surface and haunt 
our opponent! Adding to the interest of this variation is that it was for some 
time considered one of the most theoretically crucial lines of the entire Vienna 
Game. The mid-20th century American Master Weaver Adams even went as far as to 
claim it, and therefore chess itself, a 'forced win' for White! Nowadays there 
are several other, at least as theoretically viable defenses for Black, but the 
Frankenstein-Dracula variation still lurks deep within the heart of the Vienna, 
waiting for brave practitioners to resurrect it once more.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 
{This begins the 'Vienna Game', an opening popular in the 19th century. One of 
the main ideas of the Vienna is to eventually push f4 (often after Bc4 and d3) 
and transpose to a favorable form of the Kings Gambit Declined. However, as we 
shall see, Black's third move twists the game in a completely different 
direction...} Nf6 3. Bc4 ({Again, White intends after this move something like} 
3. Bc4 3... Nc6 4. d3 Bc5 {(4 ...Bb4 or 4 ...Na5 are perhaps a bit better, but 
we digress)} 5. f4 $1 {with a promising version of the Kings Gambit Declined.}) 
Nxe4 ({This is the key move of the 'Frankenstein-Dracula', the point being that} 
Nxe4 4. Nxe4 d5 {recovers Black's piece with immediate equality.}) ({For} Nxe4 
4. Bxf7+ {, see the 'Caveman Attack' lines.}) 4. Qh5 {[%cal 
Gh5f7,Gh5e5,Gc3e4][%csl Re4,Re5,Rf7] White's threats of Qxf7, Qxe5, and Nxe4 
(after, say, Qe7?) force Black's next move.} Nd6 {[%cal Gd6f7,Gd6c4] Covering f7 
and attacking the bishop on c4.} 5. Bb3 ({After} 5. Qxe5+ {,} Qe7 ({but not} 
5... Be7 $2 6. Qxg7 {,} 6... Bf6 7. Qg4 $1) {Black will have already extracted 
the proverbial fangs from this opening.}) Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e5]} ({For the actually 
quite reasonable} 5... Be7 {, see the 'Return to Sanity' lines.}) 6. Nb5 {[%cal 
Bb5d6,Gh5f7,Gb3f7][%csl Rd6,Rf7] This obnoxious move is the crux of White's play 
so far. Faced with the threat of Nxd6+ and Qxf7++, Black suddenly finds it 
difficult to defend f7 in a way that doesn't lose material.} g6 7. Qf3 {[%cal 
Gf3f7,Gb3f7][%csl Rf7] Renewing the attack on f7.} f5 8. Qd5 {[%cal Gb3f7][%csl 
Rf7] Once again menacing f7. Black must now lose an entire rook (!) but, as we 
shall see, White's sudden largesse comes at a high positional price.} Qe7 {[%cal 
Ge7f7][%csl Rc7]} ({This used to be considered practically the 'only move' for 
Black, but as we shall see later on, there is a case to be made for} 8... Qf6 $5 
{as well.}) 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 ({Now, after} 10. Nxa8 10... b6 {, White, up a 
rook, is suddenly faced with the main thematic problem of this entire variation 
- what to do with his Queen! Black intends 11... Bb7 and 12... Nd4, and how 
White plans to retreat (or, in some rare cases, not retreat) his Queen defines 
the following lines:}) {• For lines where the Queen goes to h3 (or sometimes 
g4 after ...f4), see 'Kingside Ho'; • For other Queen retreats, see 'Modern 
Options'; • For lines where the Queen stays put, see the 'Boomerang Trap'.} *

[Event "Vienna Game: Frankenstein-Dracula Variation"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Caveman Attack"]
[Black "(Bxf7+): Part One"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "vienna-game-frankenstein-dracula-variation/course/29512, variation/5178528"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Bxf7+ {One of the many odd themes of the 
Frankenstein-Dracula is how often Black loses the right to castle and how rarely 
it matters due to White's backward development. This variation is very much a 
case in point as Black's King is, outside of a few transparent traps, hardly 
bothered at all by the temporary exposure.} Kxf7 5. Nxe4 d5 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5,Re4]} 
({By far the most natural continuation - if} d5 6. Ng3 {, Black is clearly for 
choice after, for instance,} 6... Nc6 7. d3 Be7 8. Nf3 h5 $1 {, intending ...h4 
and, should White allow it, ...h3. Thus White instead engages in some tactical 
shenanigans in order to maintain the Knight on e4 for a little while longer.}) 
6. Qf3+ Kg8 7. Ng5 {[%cal Gf3f7,Gf3d5][%csl Rf7,Rd5]} Qd7 {[%cal Gd7f7,Gd7d5] 
The only move, but completely sufficient.} 8. d4 exd4 ({Also good (and perhaps 
even simpler) is} 8... e4 9. Qb3 h6 $1 {, since} 10. Nxe4 $2 {runs into} 10... 
Qe6 $1) 9. Ne2 h6 {[%csl Rg5] Begone, foul steed!} 10. Nh3 g5 $17 {[%cal 
Bc7c5,Bb8c6][%csl Rh3,Rf3] In spite of an optically airy King, Black's Bishop 
pair and central pawns combined with White's ungainly Knight on h3 give 
significantly better chances for the second player.} *

