[Comment "vienna-game-frankenstein-dracula-variation/course/29512, variation/5178527"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Bxf7+ {Here we explore one other, equally 
ineffective, attempt by White to create play against Black's temporarily exposed 
King.} Kxf7 5. Nxe4 d5 6. Qf3+ Kg8 7. d4 {[%cal Bf3b3,Gb3g8][%csl Rd5,Rg8] Again 
White relies on Qb3 to indirectly 'defend' the Knight on e4.} exd4 8. Ne2 ({For} 
8. Ng5 {, see the previous line.}) c6 {[%cal Bd5e4,Gd8d5][%csl Re4] Renewing the 
threat to White's Knight, since Qb3+ can now be answered with ...Qd5.} 9. Qb3 
{One last valiant attempt to thwart fate.} Qe7 {[%cal Be7e4][%csl Re4]} 10. Ng5 
({Or} 10. Ng3 Na6 $1 11. O-O h5 $1 {, with a strong initiative.}) h6 11. Nf3 
{White thus keeps his Knight from relegation on g3, but at a high cost, for now 
Black's pawns continue to assert themselves.} c5 {[%cal Gc5d4][%csl 
Gc5,Gd5,Gd4]} 12. Qxd5+ Be6 13. Qe4 Nc6 14. O-O Qf7 $17 {[%cal Be6d5,Bf8d6]} 
({Black's bishops, harmonious development and central control promise an 
excellent middlegame. For instance, after} Qf7 15. Nf4 Bf5 $1 16. Qe2 Re8 17. 
Qd1 g5 18. Nd3 c4 19. Nde1 {White's pieces are almost comically useless.}) *

