[White "Return to Sanity (5...Be7)"]
[Black ": Fishing Pole Attack"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "vienna-game-frankenstein-dracula-variation/course/29512, variation/5177474"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Be7 {[%cal Be8g8] With this 
move Black intends to return the extra pawn in return for a much less chaotic 
existence. However, as we shall see, with a bit of ingenuity White can still 
manage to create serious difficulties for an unwary defender.} 6. Nf3 ({For the 
newer} 6. Qxe5 {, see Caruana-Giri.}) O-O $6 ({As we shall see, this plausible 
move is significantly riskier than} 6... Nc6 {.}) 7. h4 $1 {[%cal Bf3g5] This 
is, for all practical purposes, White's most aggressive and promising 
continuation.} Nc6 8. Ng5 {[%csl Rh7] White now embarks upon a somewhat long but 
very forcing 'positional' combination.} h6 9. Qg6 {[%cal Gg6h7][%csl Rh7]} Bxg5 
10. hxg5 Qxg5 11. Qxg5 hxg5 12. Nd5 $1 {[%cal Gh1h8,Gb3g8,Bd2d3,Bc1g5] In spite 
of managing to exchange queens and having two extra pawns, Black is in a very 
precarious situation. White's threat is d3, Bxg5, and Nf6+, and amazingly 
enough, very little can be done to prevent it!} Nf5 $6 ({This at first appears 
to be Black's only real try, but there is also} 12... a5 $1 {when White might be 
a tempo short with d3, Bxg5, and Nf6+, and may have to settle for a small 
positional edge with} 13. a4 {, since Black still cannot consolidate with} 13... 
Ne8 {due to} 14. d4 $1 exd4 (14... Nxd4 $4 15. Ne7#) 15. Bxg5 {with} 16. Ne7+ 
{to follow.}) 13. d3 g4 $1 {[%csl Gf5]} ({The point of this odd-looking move is 
that g2-g4 is prevented, thus allowing the Knight on f5 to remain in defense of 
the Kingside. If instead} 13... Nfd4 $2 14. Bxg5 Nxb3 {, White mates immediately 
with} 15. Nf6+ $1) 14. Bg5 Ncd4 {[%cal Bd4b3] Seemingly warding off the worst, 
but White has still more wood for the fire...} 15. Nf6+ $1 {[%csl Rg8] In spite 
of Black's best efforts, this move still works!} gxf6 16. Bxf6 {[%cal 
Bh1h8][%csl Rg8]} Ng7 17. Kd2 $1 {[%cal Bh1h6,Ba1h1] White's plan is simplicity 
itself: double rooks on the h-file and give checkmate, and due to Black's 
undeveloped queenside, there is no easy way to prevent this.} a5 {[%cal 
Ba8a6,Ga6h6] In order to transfer the Queen's Rook over to the defense of 
Black's beleaguered Kingside.} 18. Rh6 ({Much more exact than} 18. Rh2 $6 {when 
Black can defend with} 18... Ra6 {,} 19. Rah1 Nh5 $1 {, intending to meet} 20. 
Rxh5 {with 20....Rxf6.}) Ndf5 {Forcing White's rook back to h2 at the expense of 
misplacing the formerly well-placed Knight on d4.} 19. Rh2 Ra6 {The only 
defense.} 20. Rah1 Nh5 ({Is Black surviving?} Nh5 21. Rxh5 $2 Rxf6 22. Rh8+ Kg7 
{leads nowhere, but, alas, White has one last trump.}) 21. Bxe5 $1 {[%csl 
Rh5,Rf5,Ge5,Gb3] White's bishops are absolutely dominating the Black Knights.} 
Re8 22. Bc3 Nfg7 {There is no longer any decent defense.} 23. Bxg7 Kxg7 24. Rxh5 
$18 {[%csl Rg7,Gh5,Gh1,Gb3,Rg4,Ra5,Rc8] The smoke has cleared, and material 
equilibrium has been re-established. Unfortunately for Black, White is 
positionally winning due to active pieces, healthier pawns, and significantly 
less exposed King.} *

