[Comment "vienna-game-frankenstein-dracula-variation/course/29512, variation/5177475"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Be7 6. Nf3 O-O $6 {In this 
line Black continues to tempt fate with 6... O-O, but this time White tries a 
different but no less intriguing attacking plan.} 7. O-O {This move is mostly 
noteworthy for having been tried by Nakamura, albeit in a 'bullet' game against 
Harikrishna. Nevertheless, the idea is interesting - White eschews the e5 pawn 
in order to rapidly develop an attack based on Black's awkward Knight on d6 and 
undeveloped queenside.} ({It's also worth noting that the simple} 7. Nxe5 {also 
gives White an excellent game.}) Nc6 ({Also possible, and certainly simpler, is} 
7... e4 8. Ne5 Nc6 9. Nxe4 Nxe5 10. Qxe5 Nxe4 11. Qxe4 c6 {, with 
straightforward equality.}) 8. d4 $5 {The point of White's play. Black must now 
tread with caution.} Nxd4 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Nd5 ({White intends to cause trouble 
with the two bishops in an open position. Black has a variety of defenses, many 
of which ultimately lead to similar situations, so we'll examine two in 
particular:} 10. Nd5 10... Ne8 $6 {, as played by Harikrishna, and 10... c6.}) 
c6 {This defense illustrates some typical ideas for both sides in this variation 
- White's activity with the two bishops and rapid development, and Black's 
inherently solid position and imposing pawn center.} 11. Nxe7+ Qxe7 12. Bg5 Qe5 
13. Rae1 Qc5 {Though Black's position might seem precarious, it remains a tough 
nut for White to crack open.} 14. f4 ({Also possible was} 14. g4 b6 {(what 
else?)} 15. Be7 Qxh5 16. gxh5 Nf5 17. Bxf8 Kxf8 {with an unclear endgame.}) d3+ 
{Black must act quickly to distract White from his nefarious plans on the 
Kingside.} 15. Kh1 dxc2 16. f5 Nxf5 {Practically forced, as otherwise 17. f6.} 
17. Re8 $1 {[%cal Ge8f8,Gh5f7,Gb3f7][%csl Rf7] Yikes! Black now must conduct a 
very cool but by no means hopeless defense.} d5 {[%cal Gb3d5][%csl Rd5]} 
({Avoiding} 17... g6 $4 18. Bxf7+ $3 Kxf7 19. Rxf5+ $1 Qxf5 20. Qxh7+ Kxe8 21. 
Qe7 {mate!}) 18. Be7 $1 {[%cal Ge7f8,Ge7c5,Gf1f7,Bf5e7][%csl Rc5,Rf8,Rf7] The 
hits keep coming!} Qxe7 {And Black keeps rolling along. White has nothing better 
now than 'win' the queen for ultimately too much material (rook, knight, and 
three (!) pawns).} 19. Rxe7 c1=Q 20. Rxc1 Nxe7 $17 {Black, with a solid position 
and a significant material advantage, should be at least significantly better if 
not outright winning.} *

