1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Be7 6. Nf3 ({For the newer} 6. 
Qxe5 {, see Caruana-Giri.}) O-O $6 ({As we shall see, this plausible move is 
significantly riskier than} 6... Nc6 {.}) 7. O-O {Again White plays a la 
Nakamura - Harikrishna.} Nc6 8. d4 $5 Nxd4 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Nd5 {In the previous 
variation, Black successfully navigated a treacherous situation after 10...c6. 
This time we'll see how Harikrishna initially reacted against Nakamura's 
novelty.} Ne8 $6 {[%cal Be8f6] Black's plan is to simplify with 11... Nf6 next, 
but is it a tempo late?} 11. Re1 Nf6 ({Perhaps White now expected} 11... Bf6 12. 
Bc4 $1 d6 13. Bd3 g6 14. Nxf6+ {with play on the dark squares, but Black instead 
finds a cheeky way to enter a not as scary as it at first appears endgame.}) 12. 
Nxe7+ Qxe7 13. Qxh7+ ({If instead} 13. Rxe7 Nxh5 {places the Knight on an oddly 
useful square where it prevents Bf4, White's best attacking try.}) Kxh7 14. Rxe7 
$14 ({White stands at least slightly better here due to the two bishops and 
powerful rook on e7. It would be easy for Black to go wrong with, say,} 14. Rxe7 
14... Kg6 $2 15. c3 ({even better is} 15. h4) 15... dxc3 $4 16. Bc2+ $1) *

