1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Be7 {With this move Black 
intends to return the extra pawn in return for a much less chaotic existence. 
However, as we shall see, with a bit of ingenuity White can still manage to 
create serious difficulties for an unwary defender.} 6. Nf3 {In this line we 
explore the much safer 6...Nc6 for Black, starting with a blitz game between 
Anand and Ivanchuk.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e5,Gc6d4][%csl Rc2]} ({This is a much more 
sensible alternative to the} 6... O-O $6 {of the previous lines.}) 7. Nxe5 
{[%csl Rf7]} g6 $1 {[%csl Rh5]} ({In 1935, Alexander Alekhine won a crucial 
world championship game against Max Euwe after} 7... Nxe5 $6 8. Qxe5 O-O 9. Nd5 
$1 {, and for some time thereafter this whole line was considered to be quite 
good for White. Alas, in modern times 7... g6 has been found to take a lot of 
fun out of this line.}) 8. Qe2 (8. Nxc6 dxc6 {is even less promising for 
White.}) Nd4 {[%csl Rb3,Re2]} 9. Qd3 Nxb3 10. axb3 {[%csl 
Rc1,Gc8,Ge7,Rf6,Rg7,Rh6] At first sight White seems to be doing well due to the 
open a-file, actively placed pieces and Black's dark square weakness on the 
kingside. However, White's difficulty developing the queen's bishop (normally 
Black's main problem in these lines) and Black's latent bishop pair add up to a 
roughly equal position.} Nf5 {[%cal Bd7d6]} 11. O-O (11. Nd5 c6 12. Nxe7 Qxe7 
{is awkward for White.}) d6 12. Nf3 c6 {[%cal Gc6d5][%csl Gd5]} 13. b4 {[%cal 
Bb4b5,Bb2b3,Bc1b2] Not only intending b4-b5 but also to possibly develop the 
Bishop after b3.} O-O 14. b5 d5 $10 {[%cal Be7f6,Bf8e8]} ({Anand, against 
Ivanchuk, continued with} d5 15. bxc6 {and wound up with rather little. Other 
attempts have been made to demonstrate an advantage of some sort as White from 
here (with mixed results), but in reality this position (like so many in chess) 
is simply going to favor the better player.}) *

