1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Be7 {In this line we will see 
a different, perhaps more positional approach as adopted by Caruana against 
Giri.} 6. Qxe5 $5 ({An interesting attempt to avoid the dregs of the previous 
line -} 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Nxe5 g6 $1) O-O 7. d4 (7. Nd5 {would be premature here due 
to} 7... Re8 {.}) Nc6 {[%csl Re5,Rd4]} 8. Qf4 {[%csl Gf4,Rd6] In many lines of 
this variation the White Queen finds a more or less acceptable 'home' on f4. 
Black's positional problem now is his d6 Knight, which prevents the natural 
development of his queenside pieces. Giri, however, as always, manages to find a 
path to some sort of equality.} Na5 {[%cal Ba5b3][%csl Rb3]} ({Also possible is 
the slightly wackier looking} 8... b5 $5 {.}) 9. Bd5 {Without this Bishop 
White's advantage would most likely vanish completely.} Ne8 (9... c6 $5 {is 
interesting as well after} 10. Bf3 Ndc4 $5 11. b3 Na3 {(!)}) 10. Bf3 {[%cal 
Bd4d5] White intends d5 with some minor yet possibly enduring space advantage.} 
Nc6 ({Returning the offsides knight into action. If now} Nc6 11. d5 {, Black can 
try either} 11... Nb4 {, exploiting the newly undefended c2 square due to 
White's Bd5-f3 maneuver,} ({or} 11... Bd6 $1 {, with 12... Ne5 to follow.})) 11. 
Nd5 {[%csl Rc7,Re7] Aiming to procure the two bishops.} Bd6 {[%cal 
Gd6c7,Gd6f4][%csl Rf4]} 12. Qd2 ({Thus Black has managed to swap an awkward 
knight on d6 for an equally awkward bishop! In return, White has agreed to 
misplace his queen on d2, so the position remains balanced in a rather ungainly 
way. In Caruana's game, Giri now played the slightly dodgy} 12. Qd2 12... b6 $6 
(12... Nf6) ({or} 12... Ne7 {are simpler}) {but of course managed to eventually 
draw anyhow.}) *

[Event "Vienna Game: Frankenstein-Dracula Variation"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Kingside Ho, Nunn"]
[Black "Attack, Part One"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "vienna-game-frankenstein-dracula-variation/course/29512, variation/5177486"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Nc6 6. Nb5 g6 7. Qf3 f5 8. Qd5 
Qe7 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 b6 {[%cal Bc8b7] As mentioned in the introduction, 
White is at a major crossroads of this opening here. First we will examine lines 
where the White Queen seeks a Kingside shelter on either h3 or g4 after Black 
has played ...f4 (often in response to h2-h4). Also, a quick word about Nxb6, 
both here and elsewhere: This move can and often is played at practically any 
juncture in this opening and it is rarely completely clear when it is 
appropriate to do so. However, there are a few general considerations to make: 
• A) Black's Knight on c6 almost invariably goes to d4 (after Bb7) where White 
will sometimes wish to drive it off with c3. However, if White has refrained 
from Nxb6, Black will, in reponse to c3, be loath to take on b3 as the open 
a-file will point directly to a suddenly weak pawn on a7. • B) There are a 
variety of situations where the Black Bishop penetrates to h1, capturing the 
White Rook, and is then recaptured by the White Queen. Obviously in these cases 
White would then regret having given up his Knight as it might have otherwise 
survived unless Black could afford to have spent a tempo capturing it on a8. • 
C) There are many lines where, after Nxb6 axb6, the Black pawn on b6 can be 
profitably targeted by a White piece (typically a Bishop or Queen threatening 
B/Qxb6+). As you can see, these are fairly vague guidelines. The best advice for 
White is to experiment with Nxb6 at various moments and see where it 
particularly helps or hinders your development - remember, you're up quite a bit 
of material already, so the first and most important thing right now is 
survival!} 11. d3 Bb7 {[%csl Ra8]} 12. h4 {[%cal Bc1g5][%csl Re7,Rd8] Creating 
both a threat of 13. Bg5 and also a bit of breathing room on the Kingside for 
both the Queen and in some cases (especially after an eventual ...Bxg2) the 
Rook. That said, this does involve a small loss of time as Black often wishes to 
play ...f4 in any event. In later variations we will look at what happens when 
White tries sending her majesty directly to h3 (and into a possible Black 
pawnstorm spearheaded by ...g5, ...h5, etc.).} f4 {[%cal Gf4e3][%csl Rc1]} 13. 
Qf3 Bh6 $1 {[%cal Gh8e8,Gh6f4,Be5e4] The foundations of modern 'Frankenstein' 
theory comes from the good Doctor of Mathematics, Grandmaster John Nunn, who 
examined this line in the early 70's. 13... Bh6 is one of his chief 
contributions, and the strength of the move is immediately apparent: Black 
intends ...e4 and possibly ...e3 afterwards, supported by the Bishop on h6. 
13... Bh6 also paves the way for Black's most important 'reserve' unit - the h8 
rook - to enter the game, often with lethal consequences.} 14. Qg4 $6 {As we 
shall see, this move, natural as it may seem to sidestep ...Nd4, wastes a 
valuable tempo and lands White in serious trouble.} e4 $1 {[%cal 
Ge7e1,Gd6e4][%csl Re1] This thrust is often the key to breaking apart White's 
position.} 15. Bxf4 {This move, made 'famous' in Hansen - Nunn (under 26 World 
Championship, 1974), leads to a quick a ruthless demolition of White's 
Kingside.} exd3+ 16. Kf1 Bxf4 17. Qxf4 Rf8 $1 {[%cal Gf8f1][%csl Rf1,Rf4] The 
power of Black's Rook - see comments about 13 ...Bh6 - is graphically 
demonstrated here.} 18. Qg3 Ne4 {[%csl Rf2,Rg3]} 19. Qc7+ Ke8 20. Nh3 Nxf2 
{[%cal Be7e2] As a certain English Grandmaster might say here, 'Splat!'.} 21. 
Nxf2 Qe2+ 22. Kg1 Qxf2+ 23. Kh2 Qxh4+ 24. Kg1 Qd4+ 25. Kh2 Ne5 $19 {And White is 
either checkmated in a few more moves or must give up copious amounts of 
material (and then be checkmated in a few more moves).} *

