[Comment "vienna-game-frankenstein-dracula-variation/course/29512, variation/5177485"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Nc6 6. Nb5 g6 7. Qf3 f5 8. Qd5 
Qe7 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 b6 11. d3 Bb7 12. h4 f4 13. Qf3 Bh6 $1 {Again we will 
examine 'Nunn's Move' of 13 ...Bh6, but this time with a slightly less suicidal 
defense by White.} 14. Qg4 $6 {Again, this move is probably not best, though as 
we shall see by no means simple for Black to refute.} e4 $1 {As in Hansen-Nunn, 
but White has a different, and much less flimsy, defensive setup in mind.} 15. 
d4 $1 {[%cal Bc1f4][%csl Rf4] This is the improvement!} e3 {[%csl Ge3,Re1] Black 
no longer gets a quick attack and must instead patiently probe for weaknesses 
around the White King.} 16. Nf3 {Black would like to see fxe3 by White as then 
he might have Rf8-f4 as well as a more active Bishop on h6.} Rf8 {[%cal Gf8f2]} 
({Also possible, though not quite as good as it at first seems, would be} 16... 
exf2+ 17. Kxf2 Ne4+ 18. Kg1 {.}) 17. O-O Ne4 {[%cal Ge4f2,Ge3f2][%csl Rf2] Black 
decides to try and 'force' fxe3.} 18. fxe3 fxe3 $13 {[%cal 
Gh6f4,Gf8f4,Gf4g3,Ge4g3][%csl Rf4,Rg3] The position remains unclear, with Black 
planning to infiltrate along the weak dark squares of White's Kingside (mostly 
likely either by ...Bf4 and ...Ng3, or, if White plays d5, with ...Rf4 and 
...Qc5+).} *

