1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Nc6 6. Nb5 g6 7. Qf3 f5 8. Qd5 
Qe7 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 b6 11. d3 Bb7 12. h4 f4 13. Qf3 Bh6 $1 14. Bd2 {In 
this variation we will examine what happens if White tries to head for the 
queenside 'hills'. 14. Bd2 is the most natural move, attempting to O-O-O before 
anything too serious starts hitting the proverbial fan.} ({It's perhaps also 
worth mentioning that} 14. Ne2 {isn't a terrible option either, though after} 
14... Nd4 15. Qg4 Nxe2 16. Kxe2 (16. Qxe2 $6 Bxg2) 16... e4 $1 {, it's hard not 
to be a bit nervous about White's King.}) Nd4 15. Qg4 $6 ({As mentioned before, 
this, in spite of appearing several times in master practice, is pretty much 
demonstrably inferior to} 15. Qh3 {.}) e4 {[%cal Be4d3,Ge7e1,Be4e3][%csl Re1] 
The key to Black's counterplay.} 16. O-O-O (16. Kf1 {is a fairly miserable 
alternative.}) ({Note that} 16. dxe4 {loses quickly to} 16... Nxe4 17. Ne2 Nf6 
$1 {,}) ({as does} 16. Bc3 {- which, as we shall see in the next variation, is 
an excellent move after 15. Qh3 -} 16... exd3+ 17. Kf1 Ne4 $1) e3 {[%csl 
Rd2,Ge3]} 17. fxe3 Nxb3+ 18. axb3 fxe3 19. Be1 e2+ {[%cal Gh6c1,Be2d1][%csl 
Rc1,Rd1]} 20. Rd2 Bxa8 21. Nh3 ({White could alternatively head for a somewhat 
drab endgame with} 21. Qxe2 Rf8 22. Qxe7 Kxe7 23. Nf3 Bxf3 24. gxf3 Rxf3 {,}) 
({but not} 21. Nf3 $6 Bxf3 22. gxf3 (22. Qxf3 $2 Rf8 $1) 22... Re8 $1) ({or} 21. 
Nxe2 $6 Re8 $1 {with a dodgy position in either case.}) Bxd2+ 22. Bxd2 Rf8 $13 
{[%cal Bf8f1,Bd6f5][%csl Ge2,Ga8] In spite of the sightly inaccurate 15. Qg4, it 
must be admitted that this position is probably roughly equal, with White up a 
doubled pawn and Black with certain nebulous chances based on well placed pieces 
and a dangerous looking pawn on e2.} *

