1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Nc6 6. Nb5 g6 7. Qf3 f5 8. Qd5 
Qe7 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 b6 11. d3 {In this variation we play White, because I 
think this is White's best line to play against the dreaded 'Nunn Attack'! It's 
similar to the previous variation except that our Queen runs to h3 instead of 
g4, and that, as it turns out, makes a big difference...} Bb7 12. h4 {[%cal 
Bc1g5][%csl Re7,Rd8]} f4 13. Qf3 Bh6 $1 14. Bd2 {[%cal Be1c1] Like the previous 
variation, White tries to escape to the queenside. Unlike the previous 
variation, White does not succeed, but only because something better arises!} 
Nd4 15. Qh3 $1 ({This move has yet to be tested in master practice, but there 
are some fairly concrete tactical reasons why it is superior to} 15. Qg4 {, 
which, as we have seen, has been played several times with dubious results.}) e4 
16. Bc3 $1 {[%cal Gc3h8,Gh3d3][%csl Rd4,Rh8,Gd3]} ({The point of Qh3 is that 
this interesting move is now possible. If instead} 16. O-O-O {we have lines 
similar to 15. Qg4 with Black pushing the pawn down White's chessic throat.}) 
Nxc2+ {[%cal Gh3d3]} ({In lines with 15. Qg4, Black would now have} 16... exd3+ 
17. Kf1 Ne4 $1 {, but here that would immediately fail to} 18. Qxd3 {. Black 
therefore must instead try his luck in this wild line.}) 17. Bxc2 exd3+ 18. Kf1 
dxc2 {[%cal Bb7a6][%csl Rf1] Threatening 19....Ba6+.} 19. Qd3 {[%cal Gd3a6]} Re8 
20. Nf3 $13 {Another wonky position has arisen, rife with possibilities for both 
sides, but given that White seems to have weathered the worst and remains up an 
exchange, I'd recommend this line over any of the other 'Kingside Ho' 
variations.} *

