1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Nc6 6. Nb5 g6 7. Qf3 f5 8. Qd5 
Qe7 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 b6 11. d3 Bb7 12. h4 f4 13. Qf3 Bh6 $1 {While I 
consider the previous variation to be probably White's best against the 'Nunn', 
it must be admitted that it is still quite complex and perhaps not to everyone's 
taste. However, there is one more variation to try out, and perhaps the oddest 
of all!} 14. Bd5 $5 {[%cal Gf3b7][%csl Rb7,Rc6] This quirky attempt to turn the 
tables on the long diagonal has the benefit of, if not surprise, than at least 
the virtue of being easy to remember as both sides have little room for 
variation over the next several moves.} Nd4 {[%csl Rf3]} 15. Bxb7 {White not 
only gets two pieces for the Queen but also saves the Knight on a8 from what 
once seemed certain demise.} Nxf3+ 16. Bxf3 $13 {[%cal Gf3a8,Bg1e2][%csl Ga8] 
White is 'up' two pieces and a rook for a Queen, though the Knight on a8 still 
has a fair amount of work to do before it is 'officially' extracted. Also, Black 
retains some attacking chances here based on ...e4 and what not, so the 
evaluation of this position remains, like so many others in this line, roughly 
unclear with chances for both sides and plenty of room for imaginative play.} *

