1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Nc6 6. Nb5 g6 7. Qf3 f5 8. Qd5 
Qe7 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 b6 11. d3 Bb7 12. Qf3 {[%cal Bf3h3] In this line White 
eschews 12. h4 and heads for h3 with the queen, hoping to create some sort of 
makeshift shelter against the coming storm.} Nd4 {[%cal Gb7g2][%csl Rf3,Rg2]} 
13. Qh3 ({Of course} 13. Qd1 {wasn't possible here due to} 13... Bxg2 {.}) f4 
{[%cal Gd4f5] It is particularly important for Black to throw ...f4 in lines 
where White has yet to play Nxb6 as it provides an excellent retreat (after c3) 
on f5 for his d4-knight.} 14. c3 N4f5 15. Nxb6 {Having driven the Black Knight 
from d4, this seems a logical moment to finally make this capture.} axb6 16. Bd2 
{[%cal Be1c1] In this line White's King, at least, can expect relative safety on 
the Queenside. The same, alas, cannot be said for the Queen on the Kingside!} h5 
{[%cal Bg6g5,Bg5g4][%csl Rh3] The stormclouds gather.} 17. O-O-O g5 {[%cal 
Bg5g4][%csl Rh3] Black is now already threatening to win the Queen outright with 
...g4.} 18. f3 Qg7 $13 {[%cal Bg5g4][%csl Rh3]} ({Again threatening ....g4. In 
Hawelko-Czerwonski (Lublin, 1993), White unsuccessfully tried} Qg7 19. g4 {,}) 
({but in all fairness the slightly better} Qg7 19. g3 {also leads to a difficult 
to defend position. In summary, though the computer evaluations are roughly 
equal in this variation, it remains, practically speaking, a hazardous path for 
White to tread.}) *

