[Comment "vienna-game-frankenstein-dracula-variation/course/29512, variation/5177481"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Nc6 6. Nb5 g6 7. Qf3 f5 8. Qd5 
Qe7 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 b6 11. Nxb6 {Here we examine the consequences of 
heading directly for h3 combined with an early Nxb6. Again, this makes Nxb3 a 
bit more palatable for Black, though in our stem game Kaidanov-Lputian (USSR 
Championship, 1987) White doesn't even bother ousting the Knight on d4, 
preferring instead to castle queenside as quickly as possible.} axb6 12. d3 Bb7 
{[%cal Gb7d5,Bc6d4][%csl Rd5]} 13. Qf3 ({Again eschewing} 13. h4 {in favor of a 
beeline towards h3, which perhaps makes sense given the slight loss of tempo 
involved with an early Nxb6.}) Nd4 14. Qh3 h5 {[%csl Rh3] Again Black tries to 
smother the stranded Queen on h3.} 15. f3 {[%cal Gf3g4] Kaidanov sees the storm 
coming (...f4, ...g5, and ...g4) and takes early precautions against the tsunami 
of pawns upon the horizon.} f4 16. Bd2 Bg7 ({Black could have also tried the 
'stock' plan of} 16... g5 {, 17... Qg7, and 18... g4.}) 17. O-O-O N6f5 {[%csl 
Rd1,Rh1,Gb7,Gg7] A common theme in the Frankenstein-Dracula is for White to ward 
off immediate threats to King and/or Queen only to drift into a position that 
is, though not immediately losing, difficult to play for purely positional 
reasons. This is that sort of position - Black's Bishops are currently far 
stronger dynamically than either White Rook, and White still must find a way to 
develop the dormant Kingside and eventually reactivate his nearly entombed 
Queen.} 18. Re1 {Kaidanov, ever resourceful, finds a way to untangle things a 
bit.} Kc7 ({Making way for ...Ra8 and also setting a sly trap:} Kc7 19. Bxf4 $2 
Nxb3+ 20. axb3 Qb4 $1 21. Bd2 Bh6 $1) 19. Ne2 Nxb3+ 20. axb3 {Now Nxf4 is a real 
threat, so Black carefully relocates the Queen.} Qd6 (20... Qc5 {is less 
accurate due to} 21. b4 {-} 21... Qb5 22. Nc3 $1 {.}) 21. Nc3 {Threatening, 
among other things, Nb5+.} Nd4 {Though White has made appreciable progress 
bringing his Knight into play, Black is still doing very well due to the attack 
brewing on the queenside after an inevitable ...Ra8.} 22. Ne4 Ra8 ({Very well 
timed! if now} Ra8 23. Kb1 {, Black has} 23... Nxb3 $3 {- threatening ...Ra1++ 
-} 24. cxb3 Qxd3+ {and mate next move.}) 23. Bc3 {White therefore must run the 
King to d2 and hope for the best.} Bxe4 24. fxe4 ({This opens the h6-c1 
diagonal, but there was little choice:} 24. Rxe4 Ra1+ {,} 24. dxe4 Ne2+ $1) f3 
25. Bxd4 ({Lputian has conducted the attack with great energy and imagination, 
but now makes a terrible misstep with} 25. Bxd4 25... Qb4 $2 {after which 
Kaidanov was suddenly winning after} 26. Bxb6+ $1 {. We will instead look at 
what Black could have done instead.}) Ra1+ 26. Kd2 Qb4+ 27. c3 (27. Bc3 Bh6+ 28. 
Re3 Bxe3+ 29. Kxe3 Qc5+ {would be pretty rough sledding for White.}) Qxb3 28. 
Bxe5+ (28. Rxa1 {runs into the drastic} 28... Qxb2+ 29. Ke3 Qe2# {.}) Bxe5 29. 
Ke3 {Run away!} Qxb2 ({Since} Qxb2 30. Rxa1 {is still impossible due to} 30... 
Qe2# {, White finally takes a moment to remove the troublesome pawn on f3.}) 30. 
Qxf3 Bxc3 {A picturesque position! White now has a choice of ultimately iffy 
endgames to seek refuge in.} 31. Qg3+ ({Also possible was the not terribly 
attractive rook endgame after} 31. Qe2 Qxe2+ 32. Rxe2 ({or} 32. Kxe2 Ra2+) Rxh1 
33. Rc2 Rxh2 {.}) Be5 32. Qxe5+ Qxe5 33. Rxa1 $15 {Though this endgame is 
probably objectively drawn, Black's active Queen and White's still exposed King 
suggests that this is by no means the end of White's practical difficulties.} *

