1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Nc6 6. Nb5 g6 7. Qf3 f5 8. Qd5 
Qe7 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 b6 11. Qf3 {In this game GM Zhao Jun tries a rather 
cheeky combination of an early Nxb6, Qd5-f3-h3, and forgoing d3 entirely in 
order to save a tempo via an eventual d4. Let's see how it pans out!} Bb7 {[%cal 
Gb7f3,Gb7a8][%csl Rf3]} 12. Nxb6 Nd4 {[%csl Rf3]} 13. Qh3 axb6 14. c3 Ne6 {Given 
that White has already 'cooperated' a bit with 11. Nxb6, it is therefore 
slightly surprising that Black does not simply now take on b3, followed by the 
standard plan of 15... f4 and a kingside pawnstorm. Perhaps the open a-file 
spooked him, but tempi are precious!} 15. Bxe6 Qxe6 16. Ne2 ({White stands quite 
well here as Black will now find it awkward to begin pushing his kingside pawns 
-} 16. Ne2 16... f4 $2 17. Qxe6 {.}) g5 {[%cal Bg5g4][%csl Rh3] Regardless, 
Zhao's opponent, IM Dimitry Schneider, does not shirk from the challenge and 
attempts to get his pawns going no matter what.} 17. d4 $1 {Thus White 
vindicates his decision to omit d3 earlier.} g4 18. Qh4+ Kc8 19. dxe5 Bxg2 20. 
Rg1 Bf3 {Though slightly thrown off of the 'normal' attacking avenues, Black is 
still very much fighting here and White must play very accurately to avoid a 
rapid debacle.} 21. Nd4 Qxe5+ 22. Be3 ({After} 22. Be3 22... Be4 {Zhao Jun 
played the slightly inaccurate} 23. Nb3 {(f4 is probably safest) but managed to 
eventually win an topsy-turvey affair. Suffice it to say that this position is 
extraordinarily difficult to play for either side and that the better prepared 
player will enjoy an enormous advantage here.}) *

[Event "Vienna Game: Frankenstein-Dracula Variation"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
