[Comment "vienna-game-frankenstein-dracula-variation/course/29512, variation/5177488"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Nc6 6. Nb5 g6 7. Qf3 f5 8. Qd5 
Qe7 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 b6 11. Nxb6 axb6 12. Qd3 {Here White adopts an unusual 
but interesting stratagem of simply dropping the Queen to d3 in order to save a 
crucial tempo for the development of the Kingside. This however comes at the 
costs of hemming in the queenside, something that could wind up haunting White 
in the long term.} Bb7 13. Ne2 f4 {[%cal Be5e4][%csl Gf4] As usual, this move 
remains Black's chief avenue of attack.} 14. O-O {White, having safely (for the 
moment, at least) castled, will now try and untangle the queenside.} h5 {Black 
must throw whatever he can towards the King as quickly as possible before White 
activates any queenside pieces.} 15. Re1 {Perhaps a bit too fancy, as Black now 
generates some nebulous-looking but actually quite potent threats. Therefore 15. 
f3 might well be the future of this line for White.} e4 {[%csl Rd3,Ge4,Gf4]} 16. 
Qc3 (16. Qh3 {seems to play right into the teeth of Black's pawnstorm after} 
16... g5 {.}) Bg7 {[%cal Gg7b2][%csl Rc3]} 17. d4 $1 ({White now seems a move or 
two away from some sort of sensible arrangement of pieces. For instance,} 17. d4 
17... g5 {can be met with} 18. Bd5 $1 {,}) ({and} 17. d4 17... f3 $6 {leads to 
favorable complications for White after} 18. Nf4 Bxd4 19. Qd2 {.}) e3 {[%cal 
Be3f2,Gb7g2][%csl Rf2,Rg2] But this instructive 'sweeper-sealer' pawn thrust 
comes just in time for Black to begin a very dangerous attack.} 18. fxe3 {18... 
exf2+ was too dangerous to allow.} Ne4 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Rc3,Rc1] The point of 
Black's play. White's e3 pawn now hems in both the Bishop on c1 and Queen on 
c3.} 19. Qc4 ({The more natural looking} 19. Qd3 {runs into} 19... f3 $1 20. 
gxf3 Qg5+ 21. Kf1 Nb4 $1) f3 $1 {[%csl Rg2,Rg1] Further neduding the enemy 
Kingside.} 20. gxf3 Ng5 {[%cal Bg5f3][%csl Rg1,Re1] White's awkwardly placed 
pieces now struggle to meet the simple threat of ...Nxf3+.} 21. Rf1 Rf8 {[%csl 
Rf3]} 22. Nf4 ({Also possible was} 22. e4 {, sacrificing back material after} 
22... Nxf3+ 23. Rxf3 Rxf3 24. Qd5 {with a totally unclear position.}) Nxd4 $1 
{[%cal Gb7f3,Gg7d4,Gg5f3][%csl Rf3] Literally all of Black's pieces are taking 
part in the assault.} 23. exd4 Nxf3+ 24. Rxf3 Bxf3 {White has been reeling from 
the continuous blows, but now can shed a piece to finally develop the queenside 
and reach a playable middlegame.} 25. Ne6+ $1 dxe6 26. Be3 $10 ({Amazingly, 
after all that chaos, the position is now more or less equal after} 26. Be3 
26... Bd5 27. Qd3 Rf3 28. Rf1 $1) *

