1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Nc6 6. Nb5 g6 7. Qf3 f5 8. Qd5 
Qe7 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 b6 11. Nxb6 axb6 12. Qd3 {Here we explore another 
attempt by White to save a tempo by immediately retreating to d3, though this 
time it is mixed with a completely different plan for where to put the King...} 
Bb7 13. c3 {At first this appears to be merely a misguided attempt to discourage 
...Nd4, but in fact it is part of a much stranger idea!} Nd4 $1 {Threatening, as 
usual, ...Bxg2.} 14. Qf1 {An unusual division of labor of the White Royalty now 
takes place.} Nxb3 15. axb3 Bg7 {White now confronts the question of where the 
King should reside in an particularly original manner.} 16. Kd1 $5 {Heading for 
the 'hole' on c2.} Qe6 {Black immediately plans to huff and puff against White's 
makeshift queenside home.} 17. Kc2 {Home, sweet home...} Ke7 {Allowing the h8 
rook to participate in the coming festivities.} 18. Ne2 Rc8 19. d3 Bd5 {Black's 
pieces look ominous indeed.} 20. c4 {Ungainly but forced.} b5 {Black throws the 
last spanner into the works...} 21. Ra3 {An odd looking moving with several 
purposes: 1) To guard b3, 2) To interpose along the soon to be devastated 
c-file, and 3) To give the King access to a1 (after Kb1)} bxc4 22. bxc4 Nxc4 
{The storm breaks.} 23. dxc4 Bxc4 24. Kb1 {24.Rc3 was also possible, though of 
questionable efficacy after 24...e4. In any event, Black, though a rook down, 
seems to have a alarming attack after 25...Qe4, and whether White can actually 
survive is still anyone's guess. So, in other words, a typical 
Frankenstein-Dracula variation!} *

[Event "Vienna Game: Frankenstein-Dracula Variation"]
