[Black "Prodigal Queen, Part One"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "vienna-game-frankenstein-dracula-variation/course/29512, variation/5197508"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Nc6 6. Nb5 g6 7. Qf3 f5 8. Qd5 
Qe7 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 b6 11. Nxb6 {Here and in the next variation we examine 
the (rather dodgy) consequences of White retreating the Queen all the way back 
to d1.} axb6 12. Qf3 Bb7 13. Qd1 $6 {Back so soon, dearest?} Nd4 {[%cal 
Gb7g2][%csl Gd4,Rg2,Rh1]} 14. Kf1 ({Since the Queen has abdicated her duties, 
the King must help defend the Kingside. If instead} 14. f3 $2 e4 $1 {is an 
immediate disaster for White.}) f4 {[%cal Be5e4,Bf4f3]} 15. f3 $2 {Again, this 
move only encourages Black to break with ...e4.} e4 16. d3 {[%cal Gc1f4]} exf3 
(16... e3 {was also very good/close to winning for Black.}) 17. gxf3 Bh6 {[%cal 
Gh6f4][%csl Gf4]} 18. c3 N4f5 {[%cal Gf5e3,Gf5g3]} 19. Qe2 Qf6 20. Qf2 {In 
Varga-Lalic (Croatian Championship, 1997), Black could now have continued as 
follows:} Ne3+ $19 {[%cal Bh8e8,Bd6f5][%csl Ge3,Rf1,Rh1,Rg1,Ra1] With an 
overwhelming position.} *

[Event "Vienna Game: Frankenstein-Dracula Variation"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Modern Alternatives:"]
[Black "Prodigal Queen, Part Two"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "vienna-game-frankenstein-dracula-variation/course/29512, variation/5197509"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Nc6 6. Nb5 g6 7. Qf3 f5 8. Qd5 
Qe7 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 b6 11. Nxb6 {Here we again examine what happens when 
the White Queen retreats all the way back to d1. In the previous variation 
White's defense was a bit suicidal, so we'll try and improve upon it as best we 
can here.} axb6 12. Qf3 Bb7 13. Qd1 $6 Nd4 14. Kf1 f4 15. c3 {A much better 
defensive try than 15.f3? in the previous variation.} N4f5 16. d3 Nh4 $1 {[%cal 
Gb7g2,Gh4g2][%csl Rg2] It's hard to keep the Knight down.} 17. f3 Ndf5 {[%cal 
Gf5e3,Gf5g3] Reinforcements.} 18. Qe2 (18. Ne2 {would be drastically punished 
by} 18... Nxf3 $1 19. gxf3 Bxf3 20. Rg1 Qh4 $1 {with an overwhelming attack.}) 
g5 {[%cal Bg5g4] Intending to increase pressure even further with 19... g4.} 19. 
d4 {Sacrificing a pawn to in order to exchange queens, but Black's attack will 
continue to rage.} exd4 20. Qxe7+ Bxe7 $17 {[%cal Bb7a6,Bh8e8,Be7c5][%csl Rf1]} 
({White can now play} Bxe7 21. Bc4 {to preclude 21... Ba6+. Regardless, Black 
continues to have ample positional compensation for the exchange.}) *

[Event "Vienna Game: Frankenstein-Dracula Variation"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Boomerang Trap"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "vienna-game-frankenstein-dracula-variation/course/29512, variation/5197511"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Nc6 6. Nb5 g6 7. Qf3 f5 8. Qd5 
Qe7 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 b6 {This is very much a key position in the 
Frankenstein-Dracula, and generally wherever White chooses to retreat his Queen 
to will define the way the game shapes up strategically. The one exception is 
the following line, which I've decided to call the 'Boomerang Trap', and will 
leave for to the reader to decide whom the trap is being sprung upon!} 11. Nf3 
$6 {This at first suicidal-looking move is based on several hidden tactical 
points.} Bb7 {[%cal Bc6d4,Gb7d5][%csl Rd5] How is White to extricate his Queen?} 
12. d4 $1 {[%cal Gc1g5,Bd4e5][%csl Re5,Re7,Rd8] This is how! White now threatens 
both ♗g5 and dxe5, thus forcing Black's reply.} Nxd4 {[%cal Gb7d5][%csl Rd5]} 
13. Bg5 {One funny thing about this line is that actually both Queens will now 
survive the ensuing melee.} Nxf3+ {[%cal Be7g5][%csl Rg5]} 14. Qxf3 Qxg5 {Black 
seems to now be winning a lot of material for his missing Rook, but White isn't 
going to let his Knight be captured without a fight!} 15. Bd5 {An unexpected 
reversal of roles has now taken place upon the long diagonal.} e4 {[%cal 
Bb7d5][%csl Rf3]} ({It is difficult to say for certain if this is objectively 
better or worse than} 15... Bxd5 16. Qxd5 Qf4 17. O-O Qe4 18. Rfd1 {, when Black 
will eventually win the a8 Knight at the cost of a rather technically difficult 
endgame.}) 16. Qc3 {[%cal Gc3c7,Gc3h8][%csl Rh8,Rd8] Suddenly White menaces both 
17. ♕c7+ and 17. ♕xh8!} Bxd5 17. Qxh8 {[%cal Gh8f8][%csl Rf8]} Qe7 {[%cal 
Ge7f8]} 18. Nxb6 {A fortuitously timed sacrifice, gaining two pawns for the 
piece.} axb6 19. Qd4 {[%cal Gd4b6,Gd4d5][%csl Rd5,Rb6]} Bc6 20. Qxb6+ Ke8 $13 
{This position is difficult to evaluate - White is up a significant amount of 
material, but his rooks will struggle to become active and Black's minor pieces 
could well manage to eventually combine in some frightening ways.} *

[Event "Vienna Game: Frankenstein-Dracula Variation"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Modern Alternatives: 8...Qf6!?"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "vienna-game-frankenstein-dracula-variation/course/29512, variation/5206920"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Nc6 6. Nb5 g6 7. Qf3 f5 8. Qd5 
Qf6 {This move is quite tricky, for there are many 'standard' lines that White 
can adopt where the Black Queen proves better placed on f6. However, if nothing 
else, White does have now a better version of the 'Boomerang' to fall back 
on...} 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 b6 11. Nxb6 {To be fair, this computer will tell 
you that White should just go into the 'main' lines from here, but for 
simplicity's sake we will follow the most straightforward path to an (admittedly 
slight) advantage.} axb6 12. d4 $5 {In the 'Boomering Trap' we saw that this 
move was possible (though murky) for White, but here it works even better due to 
the Black Queen no longer looming along the e-file.} Nxd4 13. Nf3 Bb7 {Seemingly 
making nonsense of White's plan...} 14. Qxd4 {Surprise! In lines where Black has 
played 8... ♕e7, this of course would run into 14... exd4+, but now it 
forcibly leads to an at least slightly better endgame for White.} exd4 15. Bg5 
Qxg5 16. Nxg5 Bxg2 17. Rg1 {While this position can be played for a win by 
either side and certainly cannot be considered a refutation of 8... Qf6, it 
nevertheless remains that White is a healthy exchange (for a pawn) up and 
Black's pawns are a bit dodgy. If nothing else, this line is a practical respite 
from the unending murk of the 'mainline' Frankenstein.} *

